revision.text:
{{Orphan|date=September 2017}}
'''Amye Everard Ball''' was the first woman in [[England]] to be granted a [[patent]]. Her patent for [[tincture]] of [[saffron]] was registered in 1637, merely 76 years after [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] had awarded the first patent. The original patent registration is held at the [[British Library]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jaffe|first1=Deborah|title=Ingenious Women|date=2003|publisher=Sutton Publishing Ltd|isbn=978-0750930314}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Evans-Pugh|first1=Christine|title=Engineering's most ingenious women (16 May 2011)|url=http://eandt.theiet.org/magazine/2011/05/ingenious-women.cfm|website=www.eandt.theiet.org|accessdate=July 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160714143004/http://eandt.theiet.org/magazine/2011/05/ingenious-women.cfm|archive-date=2016-07-14|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eandt.theiet.org/content/articles/2011/05/engineerings-most-ingenious-women/|title=Engineering's most ingenious women|last=Evans-Pughe|first=Christine|date=May 16, 2011|website=eandt.theiet.org|access-date=}}</ref>
{{DEFAULTSORT:Ball, Amye}} [[Category:History of patent law]] [[Category:17th-century English people]] [[Category:Patent holders]] [[Category:Inventors]] [[Category:English inventors]]
